LPWAN (Low-Power Wide-Area Network) is a wireless communication technology designed for,
IoT devices that need to transmit small amounts of data over long distances while consuming very little power.
LPWAN technologies are ideal for applications such as agriculture, smart cities, environmental monitoring, and asset tracking,
where devices often operate on batteries for several years.

LoRa (Long Range) is one of the most popular LPWAN technologies.
It achieves long-range communication by using Chirp Spread Spectrum (CSS) modulation and the Spreading Factor (SF).
The spreading factor determines how long each data symbol is transmitted.
A higher spreading factor (e.g., SF12) increases communication range and improves signal reliability but reduces data rate.
A lower spreading factor (e.g., SF7) provides faster data transmission with a shorter communication range.
This trade-off enables LoRa devices to operate over distances of 2–5 km in urban areas and up to 15 km or more in rural areas,
while maintaining low power consumption.
| Feature              | LoRa                      | Zigbee          | Z-Wave      |
| -------------------- | ------------------------- | --------------- | ----------- |
| Range                | Up to 15 km               | 10–100 m        | 30–100 m    |
| Power Consumption    | Very Low                  | Low             | Low         |
| Data Rate            | Low                       | Medium          | Low         |
| Typical Applications | Agriculture, Smart Cities | Home Automation | Smart Homes |
A real-world deployment in India is The Things Network (TTN) India and various smart agriculture projects in Karnataka and Andhra Pradesh,
where LoRa sensors monitor soil moisture, weather conditions, and irrigation systems over large farms.
LoRa is also used in several Indian smart city initiatives for smart metering and environmental monitoring,
demonstrating its suitability for long-range, low-power IoT applications.
